================================================================
        SPRING BOOT PROJECT STRUCTURE — FUNDAMENTALS
        What Each Part Is · Why It Exists · What Happens If Removed
================================================================


----------------------------------------------------------------
TOP LEVEL FILES — Every Spring Boot Project Has These
----------------------------------------------------------------

ProjectFolder/
├── HELP.md
├── mvnw
├── mvnw.cmd
├── pom.xml
└── src/


pom.xml
-------
    What it is   → Project Object Model — an XML file
    Created by   → Maven (build tool)
    Purpose      → Tells Maven everything about your project:
                     - What libraries/dependencies to download
                     - Which Java version to use
                     - How to build and package the project
    If deleted   → ❌ Project dies completely
                     Maven has no idea what to download or how to build
    Rule         → NEVER delete this — it is the heart of any Maven project


mvnw
----
    What it is   → Maven Wrapper script for Linux / Mac
    Purpose      → Lets you run Maven commands WITHOUT installing Maven globally
                     You run → ./mvnw spring-boot:run
                     It downloads the right Maven version automatically
    If deleted   → ⚠️ Cannot run Maven commands on Linux/Mac
                     Only matters if Maven is not installed globally on your machine


mvnw.cmd
--------
    What it is   → Same as mvnw but for Windows
    Purpose      → Run Maven commands on Windows terminal without global Maven
                     You run → mvnw.cmd spring-boot:run
    If deleted   → ⚠️ Cannot run Maven commands on Windows terminal


HELP.md
-------
    What it is   → A markdown text file
    Purpose      → Contains reference links and documentation hints
                     Auto-generated by Spring Initializr
                     Has no effect on the project running
    If deleted   → ✅ Completely safe — does absolutely nothing


----------------------------------------------------------------
src/ FOLDER — THE FULL BREAKDOWN
----------------------------------------------------------------

src/
├── main/
│   ├── java/          ← All your actual Java code lives here
│   └── resources/     ← All config and static files live here
└── test/
    └── java/          ← All test code lives here

IMPORTANT:
    This src/main vs src/test split is NOT Spring Boot's idea.
    It is a Maven standard — every Java Maven project follows this.
    Maven treats main and test as completely separate source sets.


----------------------------------------------------------------
src/main/java/ — YOUR CODE FOLDER
----------------------------------------------------------------

    This is where all your Java classes live.
    Inside this you create a base package like:
        com.example.projectname

    That package maps to a real folder path:
        com/example/projectname/

    Inside that package you put:
        MainApplication.java    ← entry point (auto-generated)
        YourModel.java          ← entity / data class
        YourRepository.java     ← database layer
        YourController.java     ← HTTP request handler


MainApplication.java — The Entry Point
---------------------------------------
    Code inside:
        @SpringBootApplication
        public class MainApplication {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
                SpringApplication.run(MainApplication.class, args);
            }
        }

    Created by   → Spring Initializr automatically
    Purpose      → This is the main() method — starts the entire application
    If deleted   → ❌ App cannot start — no entry point exists

    @SpringBootApplication does 3 things at once:
        1. Enables Auto Configuration
           → Spring automatically sets up DB, web server, JPA etc
        2. Enables Component Scanning
           → Spring scans this package and all sub-packages
             for @Entity, @RestController, @Repository, @Service etc
        3. Enables Configuration
           → Allows @Bean and config classes to work


The Base Package — com.example.projectname
-------------------------------------------
    What it is   → Not just a folder — it is a Java package
    Folder path  → maps to com/example/projectname/ on disk
    Golden Rule  → ALL your classes must be inside this package
                   or inside sub-packages of this package

    Why this matters:
        @SpringBootApplication sits on MainApplication.java
        It tells Spring: "scan THIS package and everything below it"
        If you put a class OUTSIDE this package → Spring won't find it
        That class will be invisible — annotations won't work

    This is called COMPONENT SCANNING.

    CORRECT:
        com.example.projectname/
            MainApplication.java     ← scanning starts here
            User.java                ← found ✅
            UserController.java      ← found ✅
            UserRepository.java      ← found ✅

    WRONG:
        com.example.projectname/
            MainApplication.java
        com.other/
            UserController.java      ← NOT found ❌ Spring can't see it


----------------------------------------------------------------
src/main/resources/ — CONFIG AND STATIC FILES
----------------------------------------------------------------

resources/
├── static/
├── templates/
└── application.properties


application.properties
-----------------------
    What it is   → A key=value config file (not Java code)
    Purpose      → Configure everything about how the app runs:
                     - Database connection URL
                     - Database username and password
                     - Port number
                     - JPA / Hibernate settings
                     - Logging settings
                     - Any custom settings
    If deleted   → ❌ App starts but nothing is configured
                     Database won't connect
                     Default values used for everything
    Alternative  → application.yml (YAML format — same purpose)
    Rule         → Always keep one of these two files


static/
-------
    What it is   → Folder for static web files
    Purpose      → Files here are served directly as-is to the browser:
                     CSS files, JavaScript files, images, HTML files
    Example      → static/style.css → accessible at /style.css in browser
    If deleted   → ✅ Safe — only needed if you serve web pages
                     Pure REST API projects don't need this at all


templates/
----------
    What it is   → Folder for server-side HTML templates
    Purpose      → Used with template engines like Thymeleaf, Freemarker
                     Spring fills in dynamic data and sends full HTML to browser
    If deleted   → ✅ Safe — only needed for server-side web page rendering
                     Pure REST API projects don't need this at all


----------------------------------------------------------------
src/test/java/ — TESTING FOLDER
----------------------------------------------------------------

    What it is   → Mirror of src/main/java but for test code only
    Purpose      → Write unit tests and integration tests here
    Auto-generated file inside:
        MainApplicationTests.java

    Code inside:
        @SpringBootTest
        class MainApplicationTests {
            @Test
            void contextLoads() {
            }
        }

    contextLoads() test     → checks that Spring context starts without errors
    @SpringBootTest         → loads the full Spring application context for testing
    If deleted              → ✅ App still runs perfectly fine
    Why keep it             → Good habit. As you add features, write tests here.
                               Tests catch bugs before they reach production.


----------------------------------------------------------------
JRE SYSTEM LIBRARY & MAVEN DEPENDENCIES — VIRTUAL FOLDERS
----------------------------------------------------------------

    JRE System Library [JavaSE-17]   ← NOT a real folder on disk
    Maven Dependencies               ← NOT a real folder on disk

    What they are → Eclipse / STS IDE display-only virtual nodes
    Purpose       → Show you which JARs and libraries are currently loaded
    Maven Dependencies shows → all downloaded JARs listed in pom.xml

    You CANNOT delete these — they are not real folders
    They are just the IDE showing you what is loaded in memory
    If a library is not showing here → it means Maven didn't download it yet
    Fix → Right click project → Maven → Update Project


----------------------------------------------------------------
target/ — BUILD OUTPUT FOLDER
----------------------------------------------------------------

    What it is   → Folder Maven creates when you build or run the project
    Purpose      → Stores all compiled output:
                     .class files (compiled Java bytecode)
                     Final .jar file (your packaged application)
                     Other build artifacts
    Created by   → Maven automatically on every build/run
    If deleted   → ✅ Completely safe — Maven recreates it on next build
    In .gitignore → YES — always add target/ to .gitignore
                     Never commit compiled files to Git
                     Only commit source code


----------------------------------------------------------------
THE GOLDEN RULE OF SPRING BOOT STRUCTURE
----------------------------------------------------------------

    MainApplication.java MUST be at the ROOT of your base package.

    CORRECT:
        src/main/java/
            com/example/projectname/
                MainApplication.java    ← ROOT level ✅
                User.java               ← same level ✅
                UserController.java     ← same level ✅
                sub/
                    SomeOtherClass.java ← sub-package ✅ still scanned

    WRONG:
        src/main/java/
            com/example/projectname/
                sub/
                    MainApplication.java  ← inside sub-package ❌
                    User.java             ← won't be scanned ❌

    If MainApplication is in a sub-package →
    Component scanning only covers that sub-package and below →
    All classes at the parent level become invisible to Spring →
    Everything breaks silently with no obvious error.


----------------------------------------------------------------
QUICK REFERENCE — SAFE TO DELETE OR NOT
----------------------------------------------------------------

    File / Folder              Safe to Delete?
    -------------------------  ------------------------------------------
    pom.xml                    ❌ Never — project dies without it
    MainApplication.java       ❌ Never — no entry point, app won't start
    application.properties     ❌ Never — nothing configured without it
    mvnw / mvnw.cmd            ⚠️  Only if Maven installed globally
    HELP.md                    ✅ Yes — does nothing
    static/                    ✅ Yes — only needed for web pages
    templates/                 ✅ Yes — only needed for server-side HTML
    target/                    ✅ Yes anytime — Maven recreates it
    src/test/ folder           ✅ Yes — but bad habit to remove


----------------------------------------------------------------
MINIMUM FILES NEEDED FOR ANY SPRING BOOT PROJECT TO WORK
----------------------------------------------------------------

    src/main/java/com/example/project/
        MainApplication.java        ← must exist

    src/main/resources/
        application.properties      ← must exist for DB projects

    pom.xml                         ← must always exist

    That is the absolute minimum.
    Everything else is either auto-generated help or optional.


